  "texts": [
    "In this 'debugger hallucination' scenario, <DONE>-predicted solutions were actually 11%p less likely to be plausible; this is in contrast to using actual code execution results, where <DONE>-predicted solutions are 12.4%p more likely to be plausible.",
    "Furthermore, individual runs became much less likely to be plausible: while 73% of the individual AutoSDruns would yield a plausible patch, only 63% would when the debugger was ablated.",
    "Thus, incorporating code execution contributes to the reliability of AutoSD; we later demonstrate in RQ5 that developers found real code execution results useful as well.",
    "Answer to RQ2: AutoSDcan indicate when its answers are more likely to be correct with the <DONE> token, which we also use to verify the utility of debugger use.",
    "In Fig. 5, we depict the performance of AutoSDas different underlying LLMs are used, with the x axis showing different LLMs roughly sorted in terms of number of parameters and the technical advancement of training, and the y axis showing the performance of AutoSDwhen using the LLM on the ARHE benchmark."
